name: Examine messages for Internet vs host down
info:
This Node is triggered by a ping response of false (i.e. more than 5 seconds to respond and thus either the network or the target host is offline)

 * gets how many consecutive times the ping has shown as down
 * sets internet down as true
 * Makes sure the down count is a number (belt and suspenders that could almost certainly be removed
 * If it is not a number than nothing happens
 * If it is, the it checks to see if the number of down responses has reached 6. The 6 is how many internet hosts are being examined. I assume that if we reach 6 then it is the internet and not just one or more of the total hosts that are down. If it is already at 6 then the system is treating the internet as down aleady and no further action is required.
 * If it is less than 6, then the count is incremented
 * If incrementing it has now made the count 6, it then records (in epoch time) the time the count went from 5 to 6.
 * Finally it saves the count back into a flow variable.

name: Time to report outage?
info:
This Node is triggered by a ping response of a number (i.e. between 1 and 4999 milliseconds for a ping response)

 * get how many nodes are down
 * save a copy of how many nodes are down
 * Set flow variable for whether to do a calculation and output to false by default
 * Makes sure the down count is a number (belt and suspenders that could almost certainly be removed)
 * Check if the count is greater than zero
 * If it is then decrement the count
 * check if the decremented count is 0 now and that the internetdown flag is true (this flag means the down count reached 6)
 * If it is, then the internet is up enough to then this record this as the time the internet came up and set the internetdown back to false and change the flag for whether to calculated and write the outage to Gsheet to true
 * Record the down count to the flow variable

uibuilder/Simple Example
info:
[Front-End](/uib_simple)

This flow gets a "quote of the day" from the Internet and passes it
to uibuilder. It caches the result so that if you reload the page,
you get the last result back. The quote is updated every 30 minutes
during the day and evening.

"Simple" refers to the front-end code. While the flow looks a little
complex, it really isn't. A trigger (repeating), an Internet request,
a cache and uibuilder. The link nodes loop the control output from
uibuilder back to the cache.

## Configuration

Update the files:

* `index.html`
* `index.js`
* `index.css`

According to the example(s) in the 3 other comment nodes in this example.

Press the button on the trigger to start the flow.

        break
    case 'r':

        break

        msg.exportableresults.Value = "user published"
        break
    case 't':
        msg.exportableresults.Value = "timer based"
        break
    case 'v':
        msg.exportableresults.Value = "settings update"
        break
}
return msg;

## **inputs**
### IgnoreEnvVar 
This boolean needs to be true to tell that Read Spreadsheet For Details subflow that it should use the specs passed in the msg to determine what spreadsheet to read from and what portion of data to read from.
### msg.SpreadsheetID
This is the very long string that identifies a specific google spreadsheet.
### msg.Tab
Specifies the tab name that contains the data.
### msg.ColStart
Specifies the leftmost column containing the desired data.
### msg.ColEnd
Specifies the rightmost column containing the desired data. 
### msg.MinRow
Specifies the top row containing the desired data 
### msg.MaxRow
Specifies the bottom row containing the desired data

name: Hubitat Single/Multiple Handler
Read Input from GSheet
info:
Use the GSheet node to get the a set of rows from a google spreadsheet.

# **Inputs**
### **creds**
This is the name on the gauth configuration node. How to get the details is beyond the scope of what I am going to put into an individual node instance. Some details are at [node-red-contrib-google-sheets](https://flows.nodered.org/node/node-red-contrib-google-sheets)
### **Method**
In this case using the get cells method to read a set of data.
### **SpreadsheetID**
Unused as the spreadsheet ID is passed in as part of the input msg, but if needed it would be the long spreadsheet identifier that can be pulled from the spreadsheet's URL when editing it using Google Sheets.
### **Cells**
Unused as the requested cells are passed in as part of the input msg, but if it was being manually built for a static data source the format is made of of 3 parts with specific seperators:
 * **[Sheetname]** like Sheet1
 * **[upper left corner cell address]** like A1
 * **[lower right corner cell address]** like B2

The format is **[Sheetname]**!**[upper left corner cell address]**:**[lower right corner cell address]** giving an input like **Sheet1!A1:B2**

name: index.html
info:
copy the following and paste into `index.html` ```html http-vue-loader/VueJS Example - Node-RED UI Builder

Example of loading a .vue file

Uses http-vue-loader in order to avoid a build step. Also see the Vue documentation on single file components.

This example uses a custom VueJS component called <my-component> which is defined in the file my-compontent.vue.

The custom component has two "props" (properties) that allow you to send data to it. These override the default greeting and name. By passing msg.payload.greeting and/or msg.payload.who in the msg from Node-RED, you will see the text change on-screen dynamically.

This text goes into the <slot> tags in the component. try removing this from index.html to see the default text.
```

## **inputs**
### IgnoreEnvVar 
This boolean needs to be true to tell that Read Spreadsheet For Details subflow that it should use the specs passed in the msg to determine what spreadsheet to read from and what portion of data to read from.
### msg.SpreadsheetID
This is the very long string that identifies a specific google spreadsheet.
### msg.Tab
Specifies the tab name that contains the data.
### msg.ColStart
Specifies the leftmost column containing the desired data.
### msg.ColEnd
Specifies the rightmost column containing the desired data. 
### msg.MinRow
Specifies the top row containing the desired data 
### msg.MaxRow
Specifies the bottom row containing the desired data

name: Read Device Input from GSheet
info:
Use the GSheet node to get the a set of rows from a google spreadsheet.

# **Inputs**
### **creds**
This is the name on the gauth configuration node. How to get the details is beyond the scope of what I am going to put into an individual node instance. Some details are at [node-red-contrib-google-sheets](https://flows.nodered.org/node/node-red-contrib-google-sheets)
### **Method**
In this case using the get cells method to read a set of data.
### **SpreadsheetID**
Unused as the spreadsheet ID is passed in as part of the input msg, but if needed it would be the long spreadsheet identifier that can be pulled from the spreadsheet's URL when editing it using Google Sheets.
### **Cells**
Unused as the requested cells are passed in as part of the input msg, but if it was being manually built for a static data source the format is made of of 3 parts with specific seperators:
 * **[Sheetname]** like Sheet1
 * **[upper left corner cell address]** like A1
 * **[lower right corner cell address]** like B2

The format is **[Sheetname]**!**[upper left corner cell address]**:**[lower right corner cell address]** giving an input like **Sheet1!A1:B2**
